I agree.  In fact, Jesus might have been born sometime around March or April in today's Gregorian calendar since he's a Pisces.
Nonetheless, it's the spirit of generosity, brotherhood, tolerance, and all the happiness that comes with it that matters during this season, and reminds us all that as humans we need to be more tolerant with one another in order to co-exist harmoniously together.  
"Love your brother" and "Love thy neighbor" and all that kind of stuff, and what's wrong with that?
You know, many people today are not aware that during WW-1 and WW-2, soldiers from all fronts will cease hostility and stop shooting to commemorate and reminisce happy times back home.  Nowadays, there is so much hate, anger, and hostility that people will even shoot innocent kids inside their classrooms.  That makes my heart bleed.
I wish and hope that things will get much better for us all in the coming years.
Thanks for your response.
Cheers!

Merry Chrismas to one and all !!
I don't care if they say it's politically incorrect nowadays because of Religious Equality, blah-blah.  But this is the time every year, worldwide, whether you're a Christian, Muslim, Buddhist, Jewish, Hindu, Atheist, or whatever that you enjoy Christmas break or vacation for kids and students, Christmas bonuses to many hard-working people, delightful festivities all around, the feeling of generosity, sharing, tolerance, and gift-giving, family unity and bonding, delicious food and sweets, and all because Christ was born - 'Christ'-mas.
You can not deny it.  Just be glad, thankful, and join in on the fun season.  If Jesus's birth is not celebrated, just imagine how dreadfully, horribly depressing it might be in winter and the rainy season in many parts of the world.
Joy to the world, everyone !
